description.value: Qenherkhepshef's handwriting (P. Chester Beatty III; sheet 3): the recto contains a copy of a manual for interpreting   dreams written in Middle Egyptian, in a fine literary hand of an unknown scribe (this section is columns 8-11). Qenherkhepshef's instantly recognizable, bold and highly cursive handwriting is apparent on  the verso of this papyrus, where he copied part of a recently composed poem. He also added a copy of a letter he had written to the vizier. The papyrus was later owned by his young wife's second husband  Khaemamen,  and then his son Amennakht, both of whom added their names to the recto in handwriting that is less neat than that of the original copyist of the Dream book, but much less cursive than Qenherkhepshef's (under column 10).

description.value:
P. Ramesseum B, Frame 3. Papyrus written on the recto in linear hieroglyphic script, containing the text of a liturgy in honour of Senwosret I (the so-called Ramesseum Dramatic Papyrus), illustrated with vignettes. The text is written in vertical columns with titles and some text in horizontal lines, possibly in retrograde script. This frame contains lines 64-84. The papyrus was a full-height roll.

The papyrus is part of the collection of papyri found with a bundle of pens in a chest from a plundered late 13th dynasty tomb under the Ramesseum, apparenly belonging to someone like a lector priest. Two of the papyri from the chest are in the Egyptian Museum Berlin (P. Ramesseum A and D); the objects are in the Fizwilliam Museum Cambridge and the Manchester Museum.

The papyri are very fragile, apparently due to dampness in the tomb-shaft. This papyrus was mounted on sheets of gelatin by Hugo Ibscher.

The letter comprises eleven lines of hieratic on the recto and a further two on the verso. The address is written on the bottom of the verso; this would have been visible when the letter was folded and sealed into a small package (the cracks in the papyrus are the result of the ancient folds).
